Japan, Australian Stock Futures Rise on Optimism Fed Will Act

-- B y   Y o s h i a k i   N o h a r a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-08-23T23:26:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-23/japan-australia-stock-futures-rise-on-optimism-fed-will-act-to-boost-u-s-.html
Japanese and Australian stock
futures rose after weaker-than-estimated U.S. economic data
reinforced optimism Federal Reserve Chairman  Ben S. Bernanke 
will act to support growth.  American depositary receipts of  Toyota Motor Corp. (7203) , Japan’s
largest carmaker, rose 1.1 percent from the closing share price
in Tokyo. Those of  Sony Corp. (6758) , the nation’s biggest exporter of
consumer electronics that gets 70 percent of its revenue
overseas, gained 0.9 percent. ADRs of  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL) ,
Australia’s No. 2 oil and gas producer, advanced 1.1 percent
after crude prices rose.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
September closed at 8,840 in Chicago yesterday, up from 8,740 in
Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 8,820 in Osaka
at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index rose 1.4 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index
advanced 1.2 percent in Wellington.  “The market has priced in a slowdown in the U.S. economy
to a good degree, and that’s why a series of weak U.S. economic
reports tend to raise expectations that Bernanke will do
something rather than damping the market,” said  Kenichi Hirano ,
general manager and strategist at Tachibana Securities Co. in
 Tokyo .  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. In New York, the index jumped 3.4 percent
yesterday in the biggest rally since Aug. 11. All 10 industries
in the benchmark gauge rose, with gains ranging between 1.8
percent and 4.6 percent.  Jackson Hole   Central bankers from around the world meet this week in
Jackson Hole, Wyoming.Bernanke is set to give a speech on Aug.
26. During last year’s conference, he signaled a second round of
asset purchases, known as QE2, that buoyed asset markets. The
S&P 500 rose 28 percent between Aug. 26, 2010, and Feb. 18 after
Bernanke foreshadowed the $600 billion Treasury program.  The Fed Bank of Richmond’s business activity index dropped
to minus 10 in August, the weakest reading since June 2009. The
monthly survey of producers in the region covering the Carolinas,
Maryland, Virginia and  West Virginia  corroborated factory
reports from Philadelphia and  New York  that pointed to weakness
in the industry.  The Commerce Department said sales of new U.S. homes
declined more than projected in July to the lowest level in five
months.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index dropped 12 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with a 7.6 percent drop by the S&P
500 and an 18 percent decline by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 12.1 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 11.7 times for the S&P 500
and 9.4 times for the Stoxx 600.  Crude for October delivery rose $1.02 to settle at $85.44 a
barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange yesterday.  The yen briefly declined after Moody’s Investors Service
lowered  Japan ’s sovereign-credit rating one step to Aa3, saying
“weak” prospects for economic growth will make it difficult
for the government to rein in the world’s largest public debt
burden. The yen was at 76.75 per dollar as of 8:14 a.m. in Tokyo
from 76.66 in New York yesterday after earlier falling to 76.78.  To contact the reporters on this story:
